This acts as a bridge between two incompatible interfaces, allowing them to work together.
It is especially useful for intergrating legacy code or third party libraries into a new system.

It enables classes with incompatible interfaces to collaborate witout modifying their source code.
It promotoes code reusability by allowing existing functionality to be used in new systems.
It can be implemented in two ways: 1. Class Adapter(using inheritance)
 2. Object Adapter(using composition)

 Example:
 Software uses different file formats (like CSV, JSON, XML) uses adapters to convert these into a format that thr application can work with facilitating data interoperability.

 Components:
 TARGET INTERFACE:The intreface expected by the cliet, definifing the operations it can use.

 ADAPTEE:The existing class with an incompatible interface that needs intergration

 ADAPTER:Implements the target interface and uses the adaptee internally, acting as a bridge.

 CLIENT: Uses the target interface, unaware of the adapter or adaptee details.

 WORKING:
 Client initiates a req by calling a method on the adapter via target interface.
 The adapter maps or transforms the client's req into a format that adaptee can understand using the adaptee's interface.
 The adaptee does the actual job based in the translated req from the adapter.
 The client receives the results of the call, remaining unware of the adapter's presence or the specific details of the adaptee.

 